^B@2^Y@3^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|With support for opener's major, responder has a very simple objective -- just deciding whether or not the final contract should be game (4@H or 4@S). If you have 3 or more cards in opener's major suit, that is the suit you should play in, and it is up to you to keep the auction simple and ensure that the final contract is in that suit. You should always consider the hand categories--minimum, medium, and maximum--and the The Law of Total Tricks.|CP||
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


ht|w|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMovie Maker: ^*N|cp||at|In this presentation Howard's lesson is slightly re-arranged. You can, however, read the full text of the lesson during the live session under a separate heading. Further, to refresh your memory the portions of Howard's first lesson on hand categories and The Law of Total Tricks are repeated later. You can go to the ^*BFirst Page^*N to the table of topics to review them and return back here if you wish. Otherwise, please tap the forward arrow.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


ht|l|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|On the other hand, most of the time, when you do not have support, you will bid 1NT. This simply announces you have 6-8 points and fewer than 3 cards in opener's suit. It does not promise NT distribution.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


fp|2|cp|4|at|^-

{Note that you cannot bid 2 of a new suit, because that promises a medium or maximum hand.}

^-|CP||FP||
